INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:Detected 14 issues:
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] missing_block_pointers: All four kernels use manual pointer arithmetic (e.g. offs_m[:, None] * K + k_idxs[None, :]) instead of tl.make_block_ptr. The GEMM kernels in particular would benefit from block pointers, which give automatic boundary handling, enable DPAS/TMA-friendly access patterns, and remove error-prone manual offset math.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] uncoalesced_access: In _xproj_gemm_kernel the weight B is loaded as w_ptr + k_idxs[:, None] + offs_n[None, :] * K, i.e. the RHS is accessed with the contraction dim K contiguous along rows and N strided. This is the [N,K] layout of nn.Linear.weight and produces a transpose inside the K-loop. The contraction dimension being the contiguous one for B forces strided access across N for each K step, hurting bandwidth and DPAS efficiency.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] repack_in_forward: The Linear weights (x_proj.weight [P,D], dt_proj.weight [D,R]) are passed in their stored [N,K] orientation and effectively transposed inside the K-loop every forward(). These are frozen parameters, so the packed [K,N] transpose should be computed once.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] missing_autotune: All kernels use hardcoded BLOCK sizes and num_warps (e.g. BLOCK_M=64, BLOCK_N=32, BLOCK_K=64, num_warps=4). On Intel XPU (PVC) large GEMMs prefer larger tiles (256x256x32) and more warps (up to 32). The fixed small tiles (especially BLOCK_N=32 for the xproj GEMM and BLOCK_D=8/num_warps=1 for the recurrence) leave the device heavily underutilized.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] suboptimal_tile_size: GEMM tiles are small for XPU: _xproj_gemm uses BLOCK_N=32 and the conv kernel uses 32x32. Intel PVC prefers 256x256x32 tiles for large GEMMs to saturate the systolic array.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] suboptimal_warps: GEMM kernels use num_warps=4 and the recurrence kernel uses num_warps=1. XPU large GEMMs prefer up to 32 warps; the recurrence at num_warps=1 with BLOCK_D=8 wastes the SIMD width.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] missing_grf_mode: No grf_mode set on any launch. For large-tile GEMMs on PVC, grf_mode='256' (large GRF) reduces register spills and improves occupancy.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] no_swizzling: The GEMM kernels use a plain 2D grid (pid_m, pid_n) with no GROUP_SIZE_M swizzling, so L2 reuse of the shared B/A tiles across program blocks is poor.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] sigmoid_slow_exp: The SiLU in _causal_conv1d_silu_kernel computes acc / (1 + tl.exp(-acc)) and the recurrence computes tl.exp(-dt_val). tl.exp maps to a slower path on XPU; using exp2 (with the appropriate log2(e) scaling) is faster.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] uncoalesced_access: In _ssm_recurrence_power_kernel, the B (b0..b15) and C (c0..c15) coefficients are loaded as scalars one-by-one per timestep (xproj_ptr + m*P + R + i and +R+N+i), repeated for every channel program (D/BLOCK_D = 128 programs) and every timestep. These are scalar loads with no vectorization, and the same N=16 B/C values are reloaded redundantly across all channel-blocks of the same (b,t).
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] missing_boundary_check: _causal_conv1d_silu_kernel and _ssm_recurrence_power_kernel do not mask offs_d against D, and _ssm/_conv do not mask offs_m against M on stores. With BLOCK_D=8/32 and BLOCK_M=32, shapes that are not exact multiples could read/write out of bounds. Here D=1024 and M=8192 happen to be divisible by the chosen blocks, but the kernels are unsafe for general shapes and the autotune configs may pick non-dividing tiles.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] unfused_kernels: The x_proj GEMM writes x_proj_out [M,P] to HBM, which is then read by both the dt_proj GEMM and the SSM recurrence. The dt_proj GEMM only consumes the first R columns; the SSM only consumes the last 2N columns. The dt_proj softplus output dt [M,D] is materialized to HBM only to be re-read by the recurrence. These intermediates are bandwidth-heavy on a SMALL problem.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] high_register_pressure: _ssm_recurrence_power_kernel fully unrolls N=16 hidden states (h0..h15) as separate scalar-vector registers and hardcodes N=16. With BLOCK_D wide this is heavy register usage, and num_warps=1 means low occupancy. The hardcoded unroll also breaks if d_state != 16.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] loop_invariant_code: The kernel ignores A_log entirely: the recurrence computes decay p = exp(-dt) and powers e^(-k*dt), implicitly assuming A = -[1,2,...,N], but alog_ptr (A_log parameter) is passed and never used. If the intended model uses learnable A, the decay term per state n should be exp(dt * (-exp(A_log[n]))) which is loop-invariant in t per (n) but currently substituted by a fixed integer power assumption.
