INFO:xe_forge.agents.analyzer_agent:Parsed 13/13 issues from LLM
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:Detected 13 issues:
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [5] missing_boundary_check: The _causal_conv1d_silu_kernel loads x with mask only on valid_t (time index >=0) but never masks offs_m against M or offs_d against D. With M=8192 and BLOCK_M=32 (256 blocks exactly divisible) it may be safe for M, but offs_d is also unmasked. More importantly, the SiLU store has no masking. If D or M were not tile-divisible this would read/write out of bounds. Also the x load mask omits the upper bound check on in_t (in_t < L is guaranteed by construction, OK), but b*L+in_t can index into a neighboring batch row when offs_m straddles a sequence boundary — actually it is computed per row so fine. The real risk is missing offs_m<M / offs_d<D guards.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] suboptimal_tile_size: All GEMM kernels use small tiles (BLOCK_M=64/32, BLOCK_N=32/64, BLOCK_K=64). Intel XPU (PVC) prefers 256x256x32 tiles for large GEMMs. The x_proj GEMM is M=8192, K=1024, N=160 and the dt_proj GEMM is M=8192, K=64, N=1024 — both substantial and under-tiled.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] suboptimal_warps: GEMM kernels use num_warps=4. Large XPU GEMMs typically prefer 16-32 warps with large tiles. The SSM recurrence kernel uses num_warps=1 with BLOCK_D=8, giving extremely low occupancy.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] missing_autotune: All four kernels use hardcoded BLOCK_*, num_warps, num_stages. No @triton.autotune is used, so tile/warp parameters are not tuned to the actual shapes or to XPU.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] missing_grf_mode: No grf_mode set on any kernel. For large-tile GEMMs on XPU, grf_mode='large'/'256' increases register file allocation and improves throughput.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] missing_block_pointers: All kernels use manual pointer arithmetic (offs_m[:,None]*K + k_idxs[None,:], etc.) instead of tl.make_block_ptr. This forfeits automatic boundary handling and XPU 2D block load optimizations.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] no_swizzling: GEMM kernels use a plain 2D grid (pid_m, pid_n) without GROUP_SIZE_M swizzling, missing L2 cache reuse across program tiles.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] sigmoid_slow_exp: The SiLU in the conv kernel computes acc / (1 + tl.exp(-acc)) using tl.exp. On XPU, exp2 is faster. The recurrence kernel also uses tl.exp(-dt_val) repeatedly in the hot loop.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] uncoalesced_access: In _ssm_recurrence_power_kernel the b/c state coefficients are loaded as scalars one at a time (xproj_ptr + m*P + R + i) with 16 separate scalar loads per timestep — fully serialized scalar memory access. Also each program handles only BLOCK_D=8 channels with num_warps=1, leading to poor coalescing and occupancy.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] redundant_computation: In the SSM recurrence, the state decay 'p' is recomputed as cumulative powers of e=exp(-dt) for each of the 16 states (p=p*e). This computes A_log-derived decays as a geometric series, but the model defines A = exp(A_log) = arange(1..N), so the per-state decay should be exp(-dt * A[n]) = e^n. The unrolled p*e chain assumes A[n]=n+1 which hardcodes the A_log initialization and ignores the learned A_log parameter — A_log is loaded as alog_ptr but never used. This is both a correctness concern and redundant work.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] cacheable_intermediate: self.A_log, self.D, conv/proj weights are frozen parameters; exp(A_log) and any weight-derived statistics are recomputed implicitly every forward. The model calls self.half() but A_log was created as float32; the recurrence reads alog_ptr (unused) — derived A could be precomputed once.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] dtype_input_conversion: The conv and GEMM kernels load fp16 and immediately .to(tl.float32) for every element including weights every call. While accumulation in fp32 is correct, the GEMM tl.dot inputs a and b are loaded without explicit dtype handling — a (fp16) and b (fp16) feed tl.dot which is fine, but the conv kernel converts every x load to fp32 elementwise which is fine. Ensure tl.dot uses fp16 inputs with fp32 accumulator (it does). No conversion of the GEMM operands to fp32 before dot — good. Minor: bias loads converted each call.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] open_ended: The dt_proj GEMM (K=R=64, N=D=1024) is fused with softplus epilogue (good), but the SSM recurrence kernel reloads x_conv, dt, and x_proj_out from HBM after they were just written by previous kernels. The recurrence is inherently sequential over L, but the per-timestep B/C reads from x_proj_out and the dt/x_conv reads dominate bandwidth.
