INFO:xe_forge.agents.analyzer_agent:Parsed 13/13 issues from LLM
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:Detected 13 issues:
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [5] missing_boundary_check: The causal conv1d kernel computes offs_m = pid_m*BLOCK_M + arange and indexes x/out without masking on M (only valid_t is masked). With M=B*L=8192 and BLOCK_M=32, M is divisible by 32, but offs_d for D=1024/BLOCK_D=32 is also divisible. However b = offs_m // L and t = offs_m - b*L cross batch boundaries within a tile when L is not a multiple of BLOCK_M (L=2048 divisible by 32 here, so OK), but there is no mask on offs_m >= M or offs_d >= D. More importantly the SSM recurrence and GEMM kernels lack M-dim boundary checks. The xproj GEMM masks offs_n<N but never masks offs_m<M, and writes with mask only on N. If M is not divisible by BLOCK_M these will read/write OOB.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] suboptimal_tile_size: GEMM kernels use small tiles (BLOCK_M=64, BLOCK_N=32 / BLOCK_M=32, BLOCK_N=64) and the conv uses 32x32. Intel XPU (PVC) strongly prefers larger tiles (e.g., 256x256x32) for GEMM throughput. The xproj GEMM is K=1024 contraction with M=8192 — a sizeable GEMM that is underutilizing the XMX/DPAS units with tiny N=32 tiles.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] suboptimal_warps: GEMM kernels use num_warps=4 and the recurrence uses num_warps=1. XPU large GEMMs typically prefer num_warps=8-32. The recurrence with BLOCK_D=8 and num_warps=1 gives extremely low occupancy.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] missing_autotune: All kernels hardcode tile sizes, num_warps, and num_stages. No @triton.autotune is used, so configs are not adapted to shapes/device.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] missing_grf_mode: No grf_mode set for the GEMM kernels. For larger tiles on PVC, grf_mode='256' (large GRF) improves register availability and occupancy.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] no_swizzling: The xproj GEMM uses a plain 2D grid without GROUP_SIZE_M swizzling, missing L2 cache reuse of the weight matrix across M tiles.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] uncoalesced_access: In the SSM recurrence kernel, the b/c state vectors are loaded one scalar at a time (xproj_ptr + m*P + R + i) for i in 0..N-1, 16 separate scalar loads each, with broadcasting. These scalar gathers are uncoalesced and serialize memory. Also the conv loads x with column-major-like indexing x_base[:,None]+offs_d which is fine, but the per-element scalar loads of B/C are the major inefficiency.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] manual_pointer_arithmetic: All kernels use manual offset arithmetic (offs_m[:,None]*K + k_idxs[None,:], etc.) instead of tl.make_block_ptr. This forgoes automatic boundary handling and block-pointer optimizations on XPU.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] sigmoid_slow_exp: The SiLU in the conv kernel computes acc/(1+tl.exp(-acc)) and the recurrence uses tl.exp(-dt_val); the softplus uses tl.exp/tl.log. tl.exp is slower than exp2 on XPU.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] unfused_kernels: The conv->silu output x_conv is written to HBM, then read by both the xproj GEMM and the recurrence. The softplus dt GEMM and xproj GEMM are separate kernels writing/reading intermediates. The xproj_out (size M*P) and dt (M*D) are materialized to HBM. Some of these are bandwidth-bound and could be fused (e.g., bias+softplus epilogue is already fused, good; but xproj GEMM epilogue could feed dt GEMM if tiled appropriately).
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] high_register_pressure: The recurrence kernel manually unrolls 16 hidden states h0..h15 as separate scalars times BLOCK_D, plus 16 b/c loads, keeping ~16*BLOCK_D live float32 values across the L loop. This bloats register usage and limits occupancy, while BLOCK_D=8 keeps parallelism low.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] cacheable_intermediate: self.A_log is loaded as exp via tl.exp(-dt_val) but A itself (exp(A_log)) is the discretization parameter; the alog_ptr is passed but unused in the recurrence (dskip used, alog_ptr never read). If A were used it could be precomputed; currently the parameter pointer is passed but never read — dead argument indicating either a bug or wasted launch parameter.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] missing_persistent: The xproj GEMM has M=8192 rows; with large N tiles this is a sizeable 2D grid. A persistent kernel querying gpu_subslice_count() could reduce tail quantization, but only worthwhile after enlarging tiles. Do not apply to the 1D recurrence.
