INFO:xe_forge.agents.analyzer_agent:Analyzer KB context: 6015 chars, 17 constraints
INFO:xe_forge.agents.analyzer_agent:Parsed 11/11 issues from LLM
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:Detected 11 issues:
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [5] missing_boundary_check: The _causal_conv1d_silu_kernel computes offs_m = pid_m*BLOCK_M + arange and indexes x/out without any mask on offs_m < M. Similarly offs_d has no mask < D. With M = B*L = 4*2048 = 8192 which is divisible by BLOCK_M=32 and D=1024 divisible by BLOCK_D=32, this happens to be safe here, but the SSM kernel and others also lack masks. More importantly _xproj_gemm masks offs_n but not offs_m, and stores/loads of x assume M divisible by BLOCK_M. For non-divisible shapes this reads/writes out of bounds. The xproj load of 'a' uses offs_m*K without mask.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] suboptimal_tile_size: GEMM kernels use small tiles: _xproj_gemm uses BLOCK_M=64, BLOCK_N=32, BLOCK_K=64; _dtproj uses BLOCK_M=32, BLOCK_N=64. Intel XPU (PVC) strongly prefers larger tiles around 256x256x32 to saturate the DPAS/XMX units. BLOCK_N=32 with N up to P=1056/D=1024 leaves the matrix engine underutilized.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] suboptimal_warps: GEMM kernels use num_warps=4. Large GEMMs on XPU prefer num_warps=32 (or at least 8-16) to fill the EU array. The SSM recurrence uses num_warps=1 with BLOCK_D=8 which gives extremely low occupancy (only B*128 programs each with one warp processing 8 channels).
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] missing_grf_mode: No grf_mode is set on any kernel launch. For larger tiles on XPU, grf_mode='256' (large GRF) improves register availability and reduces spills.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] no_swizzling: Both GEMM kernels use a plain 2D grid (pid_m, pid_n) with no GROUP_SIZE_M swizzling. This leads to poor L2 cache reuse of the weight matrix across program blocks on XPU.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] missing_autotune: All four kernels have hardcoded BLOCK sizes, num_warps, and num_stages. No @triton.autotune is used. Given fixed shapes (D=1024, P=1056, M=8192) autotuning would find much better tile/warp/stage combinations, especially for the underutilized GEMMs and the SSM kernel.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] uncoalesced_access: In _ssm_recurrence_power_kernel the per-step loads of b0..b15 and c0..c15 are 32 separate scalar tl.load operations per time step (xproj_ptr + m*P + R + i). These are scalar broadcast loads of the same B/C vector that is shared across all D channels; they are reloaded every program (every pid_d) and every time step, hugely amplifying memory traffic and serializing memory access.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] redundant_computation: The SSM recurrence reloads the same B and C vectors (xproj_ptr offsets R..R+N and R+N..R+2N) for every pid_d program (D/BLOCK_D = 128 programs per batch with BLOCK_D=8). These values are independent of the channel index d, so each token's B/C is read 128 times redundantly. Also 'p = e; p=p*e...' recomputes the geometric power chain that only depends on dt, but dt depends on channel d so this is per-channel; however B/C loads are clearly channel-independent.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] sigmoid_slow_exp: The SiLU activation in _causal_conv1d_silu_kernel computes silu = acc/(1+tl.exp(-acc)) using tl.exp. On XPU tl.math.exp2 is faster. Same applies to e = tl.exp(-dt_val) in the SSM kernel and tl.exp in softplus.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] manual_pointer_arithmetic: All kernels use manual offset arithmetic (offs_m[:,None]*K + k_idxs[None,:], etc.) instead of tl.make_block_ptr. This forgoes automatic boundary handling and TMA-style descriptor optimizations on XPU.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] open_ended: The SSM recurrence kernel hardcodes N=16 with fully unrolled h0..h15 state and 32 scalar loads per step, and uses BLOCK_D=8 with num_warps=1, giving extremely low arithmetic intensity and occupancy. This is the dominant serial kernel (sequential over L=2048).
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:============================================================
